body:
Since python 3.7, builtin dict is guaranteed to keep insertion order, so use dict on python 3.7 or later instead.

Stdlib enum.Enum supports an iterable of `(name, value)` even since python 3.4, so a list of `(name, value)` pairs is good enough.

comment_data.body: So practically we only use `__Pyx_EnumMeta` in Python<3.4 (but it's defined at the top level because cdef classes have to be). Therefore I think `__Pyx_OrderedDict = dict` is never used and we could simplify this and only do the `OrderedDict` import for Python<3.4 (and leave it uninitialised otherwise)
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -6,7 +6,11 @@ cdef extern from *:
     int PY_VERSION_HEX
 
 cdef object __Pyx_OrderedDict
-from collections import OrderedDict as __Pyx_OrderedDict
+
+if PY_VERSION_HEX >= 0x03070000:

commit.message:
Avoid to import OrderedDict on 3.7 or later

Since python 3.7, builtin dict is guaranteed to keep insertion order.

Remove unnecessary OrderedDict

enum.Enum supports an iterable of (name, value) even since python 3.4.

Use dict on CPython 3.6

dict on PyPy started to be ordered even before CPython, only CPython
and PyPy are supported by Cython now, so it's fine to use dict on
Python 3.6
